From cou.: 51 Z
From Soup: 51 A summary of the enhancements for several analytes using eqn (2) is shown in Fig. 2 . The average enhancement for all of the elements shown in the figure is 4.5 ± 0.4; and in no instance was a loss in intensity observed as a result of using the dry calibrator to optimize the analytical conditions of the plasma or analyzer system. The Sn and W were included in the suite of elements in Fig. 2 to demonstrate that the tuning masses were not enhanced to a greater extent than other masses.
 ###### 
From cou.: 52 +
From Soup: 52 Si suffers from a significant 28 N 2 background signal because of entrained atmospheric gasses and the HNO 3 matrix as well as 28 CO. The other isotopes of Si are much less abundant and also suffer from polyatomic interferences, e.g. , 29 CO and 30 NO. However, the dry optimized parameter set was able to produce a Si + signal that was greater than the background while the Si + signal with the wet plasma was indistinguishable from the background. This prevented calculations of an enhancement factor for Si. Br was also monitored with the ETV firing but failed to produce a significant signal using either parameter set. This was probably caused by the volatilization of HBr and loss during the 300 °C heating step before data collection had begun. The nearly element independent enhancement indicates that the dry optimization served to better sample the plasma and focus the resulting ion stream in the ion optics region. This may be a result of the physical changes in the plasma ( e.g. plasma pulling back into the torch) at lower applied powers and no solvent load. By sampling the plasma more efficiently, all of the ions signals were enhanced without bias toward specific properties such as mass or ionization potential.
